<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-701-672  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 701 672.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  August 1990 v7 n8 p36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Brazil eases controls on computer imports: four decades ofprotectionism may be ending.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>St.Clair, Melanie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Brazil will soon relax some of its restrictions on computerimports, opening the market to foreign multinational companies inan attempt to help modernize its industrial sector.andP;  Many of therestrictions expected to be eased are the result of the NationalInformatics Policy, a protectionist law instituted in the 1970sthat severely limited the licensing and import of products classedas functionally equivalent to products either already underdevelopment domestically or being reserved for domesticdevelopment.andP;  Relaxation of the restrictions is going more slowlythan expected, but Novell received approval for legal shipment ofNetWare into Brazil in Jan 1990.andP;  The market for networkingproducts is characterized as extremely ripe.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Novell Inc. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    NOVL.andO;Product:   NetWare (Network operating system) (marketing).andO;Topic:     International TradeRestraint of TradeGovernment RegulationBrazilNetworks.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>